{{Infobox ancient site |name = Munhata |alternate_name = Horvat Minha, Khirbet Munhata |image = |alt = |caption = |map_type = Israel |map_alt = {{convert|215|m|ft}} below sea level |location = Israel |coordinates = {{coord|32.652383|35.463181|display=inline}} |type = Tell |builder = |material = |built = ca. 8300 [[Before Christ|BC]] |abandoned = ca. 6000 [[Before Christ|BC]] |cultures = [[PPNB]], [[Neolithic]], [[Chalcolithic]] |epochs = |excavations = 1962-1963 |archaeologists = [[Jean Perrot]] |condition = |public_access = yes |management = }} '''Munhata''' ('''Horvat Minha''' or '''Khirbet Munhata''') is an [[archaeology|archaeological]] site {{convert|11|km|mi}} south of [[Lake Tiberias]], [[Israel]] on the north bank and near the outlet of [[Nahal Tavor]] (Tabor Stream) on a terrace {{convert|215|m|ft}} below sea level.<ref name="MeyersResearch1997">{{cite book|author1=Eric M. Meyers|author2=American Schools of Oriental Research|title=The Oxford encyclopedia of archaeology in the Near East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KYzrAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=25 April 2011|year=1997|publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref>
==Excavations== The area of {{convert|2000|m2|ft2}} in the [[Jordan Valley (Middle East)|Jordan Valley]] was first excavated in 1962 by [[Jean Perrot]]. The deposits on site were {{convert|3|m|ft}} deep and divided up into six distinct layers of occupation. These have been divided into [[PPNB]] aceramic during levels six to three, with later [[Neolithic]] and [[Chalcolithic]], [[Yarmukian Culture|Yarmukian]] and Wadi Rabah cultures in levels two and one.
==Construction== Buildings in the earlier stages had stone, paved or plastered floors made of mud bricks on stone foundations with remains of hearths and other stone structures. The north walls of buildings contained a plastered niche, a feature found in a similar room in [[Jericho]].<ref name="Moore"/> The [[PPNB]] levels also revealed an unusual circular [[courtyard]] structure with rooms radiating out from it and a large platform with channels cut in it associated with a pebble lined trough, presumably used for craft purposes.<ref name="PeregrineEmber2002">{{cite encyclopedia|editor1-first=Peter Neal|editor1-last=Peregrine|editor1-link=Peter N. Peregrine|editor2-first=Melvin|editor2-last=Ember|editor2-link=Melvin Ember|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Prehistory|volume=8 : South and Southwest Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C-TQpUtI-dgC&pg=PA52|accessdate=25 April 2011|year=2002|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-0-306-46262-7|pages=52}}</ref> The Yarmoukian phase continued with round buildings which developed into rectangular ones in the Rabah phase.<ref name="Moore">{{cite book|last=Moore|first=A.M.T.|title=The Neolithic of the Levant|publisher=Oxford University, Unpublished Ph.D. Thesis|year=1978|pages=176–178|url=http://ancientneareast.tripod.com/109.html}}</ref> A major break in settlement was detected between levels three and two, where the early levels were covered over with sandy soil.
==Culture== Various flint tools and arrowheads were recovered from the site. Arrowheads had distinctive tangs (some barbed) with wings and pointed shoulders, some were diamond or leaf shaped and a few were notched. Finely denticulated [[sickle]] blades were found in large numbers with other tools including end scrapers, blades, burins and borers. One piece of [[obsidian]] was found in level six that originated from the same place as a piece from [[El Khiam]]. Grinding tools were also found including [[pestle and mortar]]s of basalt or limestone, polishers, rubbers and grooved stones. [[Stoneware]] vessels were found along with a few greenstone beads.<ref name="Moore"/> The site was also notable for finds of clay figurines of males, females and animals.
==Dating== [[Radio-carbon dating]] of the site had large stated errors due to problematic dating materials but gave dates between ca. 7210 and 5420 [[Before Christ|BC]]. These provide a vague suggestion of the age of the site. [[Typology (archaeology)|Typological]] comparisons have been made of various artifacts highlighting a certain regional variation with more elaborate design arrowheads and less pressure flaking. This equates generally with the PPNB stages of Jericho and [[Beidha]] suggesting that occupations overlapped with these sites and a date of occupation during the middle and late 7th millennium BC.<ref name="Moore"/>
==Further reading== * {{cite book|author=Jean Perrot|title=Les deux premières campagnes de fouilles a Munhatta, 1962-1963: premiers résultats|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1S05HQAACAAJ|accessdate=25 April 2011|year=1964|publisher=Librairie Orientale P. Geuthner}} * Perrot, Jean., La troisieme campagne de fouilles a Munhata (1964), Syria 43, 1966. * {{cite book|author1=Yosef Garfinkel |author2=Yuval Goren |title=The pottery assemblages of the Sha'ar Hagolan and Rabah stages of Munhata|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IjwpOgAACAAJ|accessdate=25 April 2011|year=1992|publisher=Publié avec le concours de la DGRCST}} * {{cite book|author=Yosef Garfinkel|title=Human and animal figurines of Munhata|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2APjAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=25 April 2011|year=1995|publisher=Association Paléorient}} * {{cite book|author=Avi Gopher|title=The flint assemblages of Munhata: final report|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qsH0OQAACAAJ|accessdate=25 April 2011|year=1989|publisher=Association Paléorient}}
